2
00:00:06.630 --> 00:00:09.500
Welcome, sweet prince, toLondon, to your chamber.

3
00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:12.170
Welcome, dear cousin, mythoughts' sovereign.

4
00:00:21.430 --> 00:00:24.470
The weary way hath madeyou melancholy.

5
00:00:24.470 --> 00:00:28.630
No, Uncle, but our crosseson the way

6
00:00:28.630 --> 00:00:31.970
have made it tedious,wearisome, and heavy.

7
00:00:36.170 --> 00:00:38.170
I want more uncles here towelcome me.

8
00:00:41.330 --> 00:00:45.500
Sweet prince, the untaintedvirtue of your years

9
00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:48.500
hath not yet dived intothe world's deceit.

10
00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:52.000
Nor more can youdistinguish of a man thanof his outward show,

11
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:53.300
which God, he knows,

12
00:00:53.300 --> 00:00:55.900
seldom or never jumpethwith the heart.

13
00:00:55.900 --> 00:00:59.070
Those uncles which youwant were dangerous.

14
00:00:59.070 --> 00:01:01.330
Your grace attended totheir sugared words

15
00:01:01.330 --> 00:01:04.270
but looked not on thepoison of their hearts.

16
00:01:04.270 --> 00:01:07.500
God keep you from them andfrom such false friends.

17
00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:10.700
God keep me from falsefriends.

18
00:01:11.870 --> 00:01:13.430
But they were none.

19
00:01:14.870 --> 00:01:17.600
My lord, the mayor ofLondon comes to greet you.

20
00:01:17.600 --> 00:01:20.770
God bless your grace withhealth and happy days.

21
00:01:20.770 --> 00:01:24.200
I thank you, good my lord,and thank you all.

22
00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:34.200
I thought my mother and mybrother York

23
00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:36.030
would long ere this havemet us on the way.

24
00:01:37.170 --> 00:01:40.330
Fie, what a slug isHastings, that he comesnot to tell us

25
00:01:40.330 --> 00:01:42.300
whether they will come orno.

26
00:01:43.570 --> 00:01:46.000
And in good time, herecomes the sweating lord.

27
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:47.400
Welcome, my lord.

28
00:01:49.070 --> 00:01:50.930
What, will our mothercome?

29
00:01:50.930 --> 00:01:53.970
On what occasion, God heknows, not I,

30
00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:56.030
the queen your mother andyour brother York

31
00:01:56.030 --> 00:01:57.730
have taken sanctuary.

32
00:01:57.730 --> 00:01:59.800
The tender prince wouldfain have come with me

33
00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:01.000
to meet your grace

34
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.430
but by his mother wasperforce withheld.

35
00:02:03.430 --> 00:02:06.530
Fie, what an indirect andpeevish course

36
00:02:06.530 --> 00:02:07.870
is this of hers.

37
00:02:07.870 --> 00:02:10.600
Lord cardinal, will yourgrace persuade the queen

38
00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:11.930
to send the Duke of York

39
00:02:11.930 --> 00:02:13.800
unto his princely brotherpresently?

40
00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:16.100
If she deny, LordHastings, go with him

41
00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:18.200
and from her jealous armspluck him perforce.

42
00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:24.300
My lord of Buckingham, ifmy weak oratory

43
00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:27.270
can from his mother winthe Duke of York,

44
00:02:27.270 --> 00:02:29.830
anon expect him here.

45
00:02:29.830 --> 00:02:35.000
But if she be obdurate tomild entreaties,

46
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:36.500
God in Heaven forbid

47
00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:40.000
we should infringe the holyprivilege of blessedsanctuary.

48
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:45.070
Not for all this landwould I be guilty of sodeep a sin.

49
00:02:45.070 --> 00:02:47.500
You are too senseless--obstinate, my lord,

50
00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:50.300
too ceremonious andtraditional.

51
00:02:50.300 --> 00:02:53.770
Weigh it but with thegrossness of this age.

52
00:02:53.770 --> 00:02:55.800
You break not sanctuary inseizing him.

53
00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:58.530
The benefit thereof isalways granted

54
00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:01.200
to those whose dealingshave deserved the place

55
00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:04.130
and those who have the witto claim the place.

56
00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:06.630
This prince hath neitherclaimed it nor deserved it

57
00:03:06.630 --> 00:03:08.930
and therefore, in mineopinion, cannot have it.

58
00:03:08.930 --> 00:03:11.930
Then taking him fromthence that is not there,

59
00:03:11.930 --> 00:03:14.970
you break no privilege norcharter there.

60
00:03:14.970 --> 00:03:17.570
Oft have I heard ofsanctuary men,

61
00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:20.770
but sanctuary children...

62
00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:26.800
Never till now.

63
00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:37.270
My lord, you shallo'errule my mind for once.

64
00:03:38.670 --> 00:03:41.500
Come on, Lord Hastings;will you go with me?

65
00:03:43.270 --> 00:03:45.300
I go, my lord.

66
00:03:46.370 --> 00:03:48.070
Good lords...

67
00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:52.570
Make all the speedy hasteyou may.

68
00:04:00.100 --> 00:04:01.700
Say, Uncle Gloucester...

69
00:04:03.700 --> 00:04:04.900
If our brother come,

70
00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:06.900
where shall we sojourntill our coronation?

71
00:04:06.900 --> 00:04:11.200
Where it seems best untoyour royal self.

72
00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:13.700
If I may counsel you, someday or two,

73
00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:16.570
your highness shall reposeyou at the Tower,

74
00:04:16.570 --> 00:04:19.530
then where you please andshall be thought most fit

75
00:04:19.530 --> 00:04:21.770
for your best health andrecreation.

76
00:04:21.770 --> 00:04:24.830
I do not like the tower ofany place.

77
00:04:32.830 --> 00:04:35.430
Did Julius Caesar buildthat place, my lord?

78
00:04:35.430 --> 00:04:38.300
He did, my gracious lord,begin that place,

79
00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:41.000
which since succeedingages have re-edified.

80
00:04:42.230 --> 00:04:45.300
Is it upon record or elsereported successively

81
00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:46.870
from age to age, he builtit?

82
00:04:46.870 --> 00:04:50.430
Upon record, my graciouslord.

83
00:04:50.430 --> 00:04:54.100
But say, my lord, it werenot registered,

84
00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:57.000
methinks the truth shouldlive from age to age,

85
00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.400
as 'twere retailed to allposterity,

86
00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:01.630
even to the generalall-ending day.

87
00:05:02.630 --> 00:05:05.930
So wise so young, theysay, do ne'er live long.

88
00:05:05.930 --> 00:05:06.930
What say you, Uncle?

89
00:05:06.930 --> 00:05:11.470
I say without characters,fame lives long.

90
00:05:11.470 --> 00:05:14.830
That Julius Caesar was afamous man.

91
00:05:14.830 --> 00:05:17.530
With what his valor didenrich his wit,

92
00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:20.930
his wit set down to makehis valor live.

93
00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:23.530
Death makes no conquest ofthis conqueror,

94
00:05:23.530 --> 00:05:27.430
for now he lives in fame,though not in life.

95
00:05:27.430 --> 00:05:29.700
I'll tell you what, mycousin Buckingham.

96
00:05:29.700 --> 00:05:31.270
What, my gracious lord?

97
00:05:31.270 --> 00:05:33.100
An if I live until I be aman,

98
00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:35.170
I'll win our ancient rightin France again

99
00:05:35.170 --> 00:05:37.970
or die a soldier as Ilived a king.

100
00:05:38.970 --> 00:05:41.970
Short summers lightly havea forward spring.

101
00:05:41.970 --> 00:05:44.900
Now in good time, herecomes the Duke of York.

102
00:05:44.900 --> 00:05:46.370
Richard of York.

103
00:05:46.370 --> 00:05:49.300
How fares our lovingbrother?

104
00:05:49.300 --> 00:05:52.870
Well, my dread lord; somust I call you now.

105
00:05:54.370 --> 00:05:59.300
Aye, brother, to ourgrief, as it is yours.

106
00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:02.870
Too late he died thatmight have kept that title

107
00:06:02.870 --> 00:06:07.430
which by his death hathlost much majesty.

108
00:06:08.830 --> 00:06:11.830
How fares our cousin,noble lord of York?

109
00:06:11.830 --> 00:06:14.130
I thank you, gentle uncle.

110
00:06:14.130 --> 00:06:18.000
O, my lord, you said that idleweeds are fast in growth.

111
00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.500
The prince my brother hathoutgrown me far.

112
00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:22.230
He hath, my lord.

113
00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:24.030
And therefore, is he idle?

114
00:06:25.830 --> 00:06:28.470
O, my fair cousin, I mustnot say so.

115
00:06:28.470 --> 00:06:31.000
Then is he more beholdingto you than I.

116
00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.430
He may command me as mysovereign,

117
00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:35.970
but you have power in meas in a kinsman.

118
00:06:35.970 --> 00:06:37.970
I pray you, uncle, give methis dagger.

119
00:06:37.970 --> 00:06:40.400
My dagger, little cousin?

120
00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:41.770
With all my heart.

121
00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:43.470
A beggar, brother?

122
00:06:43.470 --> 00:06:46.100
Of my kind uncle, that Iknow will give

123
00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:48.930
and being but a toy, whichis no grief to give.

124
00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:51.470
A greater gift than thatI'll give my cousin.

125
00:06:51.470 --> 00:06:52.600
A greater gift.

126
00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:54.570
Then that's the sword toit.

127
00:06:54.570 --> 00:06:57.630
Aye, gentle cousin, wereit light enough.

128
00:06:57.630 --> 00:07:00.770
O, then I see you will butpart with light gifts.

129
00:07:00.770 --> 00:07:02.900
In weightier things,you'll say a beggar nay.

130
00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:07.630
It is too heavy for yourgrace to wear.

131
00:07:07.630 --> 00:07:09.700
I weigh it lightly, wereit heavier.

132
00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:12.030
What? Would you have myweapon, little lord?

133
00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:14.200
I would, that I mightthank you as you call me.

134
00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:15.200
How?

135
00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:16.530
Little.

136
00:07:19.930 --> 00:07:23.000
My lord of York will stillbe cross in talk.

137
00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:28.730
Uncle, your grace knowshow to bear with him.

138
00:07:28.730 --> 00:07:31.100
You mean to bear me, notto bear with me.

139
00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:33.630
Uncle, my brother mocksboth you and me.

140
00:07:33.630 --> 00:07:35.830
Because that I am littlelike an ape,

141
00:07:35.830 --> 00:07:38.400
he thinks that you shouldbear me on your shoulders.

142
00:07:43.670 --> 00:07:46.430
With what a sharp-providedwit he reasons.

143
00:07:46.430 --> 00:07:48.400
To mitigate the scorn hegives his uncle,

144
00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:50.730
he prettily and aptlytaunts himself.

145
00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:52.570
So cunning and so young iswonderful.

146
00:07:52.570 --> 00:07:55.030
My lord, will it pleaseyou pass along?

147
00:07:55.030 --> 00:07:57.670
Myself and my good cousinBuckingham will to your mother

148
00:07:57.670 --> 00:08:00.600
to entreat of her to meetyou at the Tower andwelcome you.

149
00:08:00.600 --> 00:08:03.570
What? Will you go unto theTower, my lord?

150
00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:06.930
My lord protector needswill have it so.

151
00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:09.670
I shall not sleep in quietat the Tower.

152
00:08:09.670 --> 00:08:11.270
Why? What should you fear?

153
00:08:11.270 --> 00:08:14.300
Marry, my uncle Clarence'angry ghost.

154
00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:16.900
My grandam told me he wasmurdered there.

155
00:08:16.900 --> 00:08:18.800
I fear no uncles dead.

156
00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:21.630
Nor none that live, Ihope.

157
00:08:21.630 --> 00:08:24.100
An if they live, I hope Ineed not fear.

158
00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:27.430
But come, my lord.

159
00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:30.470
With a heavy heart,thinking on them,

160
00:08:30.470 --> 00:08:32.930
go I unto the Tower.

161
00:08:48.330 --> 00:08:50.170
Think you, my lord, thislittle prating York

162
00:08:50.170 --> 00:08:52.500
was not incensed by hissubtle mother

163
00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:56.130
to taunt and scorn youthus opprobriously?

164
00:08:56.130 --> 00:08:58.200
No doubt, no doubt.

165
00:08:58.200 --> 00:09:00.630
O, 'tis a parlous boy:

166
00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:04.530
bold, quick, ingenious,forward, capable.

167
00:09:04.530 --> 00:09:07.070
He is all the mother'sfrom the top to toe.

168
00:09:07.070 --> 00:09:10.230
Well, let them rest.

169
00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:11.600
Come hither, Catesby.

170
00:09:17.130 --> 00:09:19.600
Thou art sworn as deeplyto effect what we intend

171
00:09:19.600 --> 00:09:22.870
as closely to conceal whatwe impart.

172
00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:24.000
What think'st thou?

173
00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:25.270
Is it not an easy matter

174
00:09:25.270 --> 00:09:27.900
to make William LordHastings of our mind

175
00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:29.730
for the installment ofthis noble duke

176
00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:32.200
in the seat royal of thisfamous isle?

177
00:09:33.600 --> 00:09:36.070
He for his father's sakeso loves the prince

178
00:09:36.070 --> 00:09:39.200
that he will not be won toaught against him.

179
00:09:41.330 --> 00:09:42.400
What think'st thou, then,of Stanley?

180
00:09:42.400 --> 00:09:44.100
What will he?

181
00:09:44.100 --> 00:09:46.500
He will do all in all asHastings doth.

182
00:09:49.270 --> 00:09:51.870
Well, then, no more butthis.

183
00:09:51.870 --> 00:09:53.770
Go, gentle Catesby.

184
00:09:53.770 --> 00:09:57.130
And as it were far off,sound thou Lord Hastings,

185
00:09:57.130 --> 00:09:59.570
how he doth stand affectedto our purpose.

186
00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:01.200
And summon him tomorrow tothe Tower

187
00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:02.370
to sit about thecoronation.

188
00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:04.030
If thou dost find himtractable to us,

189
00:10:04.030 --> 00:10:06.400
encourage him, and tellhim all our reasons.

190
00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:11.170
If he be leaden, icy-cold,unwilling,

191
00:10:11.170 --> 00:10:14.200
be thou so too and sobreak off the talk

192
00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:16.430
and give us notice of hisinclination,

193
00:10:16.430 --> 00:10:18.930
for we tomorrow holddivided councils

194
00:10:18.930 --> 00:10:22.000
wherein thyself shallhighly be employed.

195
00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:23.970
Commend me to LordHastings.

196
00:10:23.970 --> 00:10:25.600
Tell him, Catesby,

197
00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:28.100
his ancient knot ofdangerous adversaries

198
00:10:28.100 --> 00:10:31.200
tomorrow are let blood atPomfret Castle.

199
00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:33.900
And bid my lord for joy ofthis good news

200
00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:37.370
give Mistress Shore onegentle kiss the more.

201
00:10:37.370 --> 00:10:40.870
Good Catesby, go; effectthis business soundly.

202
00:10:40.870 --> 00:10:44.070
My good lords both, withall the heed I can.

203
00:10:44.070 --> 00:10:46.200
Shall we hear from you,Catesby, ere we sleep?

204
00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:48.130
You shall, my lord.

205
00:10:48.130 --> 00:10:51.070
At Crosby Place, thereshall you find us both.

206
00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:57.230
Now, my lord, what shallwe do

207
00:10:57.230 --> 00:11:01.770
if we perceive LordHastings will not yield toour complots?

208
00:11:01.770 --> 00:11:03.570
Chop off his head, man.

209
00:11:05.100 --> 00:11:08.630
Somewhat we will do.

210
00:11:08.630 --> 00:11:11.030
And look, when I am king,

211
00:11:11.030 --> 00:11:14.070
claim thou of me theearldom of Hereford

212
00:11:14.070 --> 00:11:15.930
and all the movables

213
00:11:15.930 --> 00:11:18.130
whereof the king mybrother was possessed.

214
00:11:20.770 --> 00:11:24.770
I'll claim that promise atyour grace's hands.

215
00:11:24.770 --> 00:11:27.570
And look to have ityielded with all kindness.

216
00:11:30.770 --> 00:11:32.270
Come, let us sup betimes,

217
00:11:32.270 --> 00:11:36.370
that afterwards, we may digestour complots in some form.

218
00:11:42.730 --> 00:11:43.770
My lord.

219
00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:47.330
My lord.

220
00:11:47.330 --> 00:11:49.470
Who knocks?

221
00:11:49.470 --> 00:11:51.130
One from the Lord Stanley.

222
00:12:01.030 --> 00:12:02.800
What is't o'clock?

223
00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:04.170
Upon the stroke of four.

224
00:12:07.130 --> 00:12:10.730
Cannot my Lord Stanleysleep these tedious nights?

225
00:12:10.730 --> 00:12:12.400
So it appears by that Ihave to say.

226
00:12:13.630 --> 00:12:16.100
First, he commends him tothe noble sir.

227
00:12:16.100 --> 00:12:17.270
And what then?

228
00:12:17.270 --> 00:12:20.230
Then sends upon yourlordship that this night,

229
00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:24.970
he dreamt the boar hadrazed off his helm.

230
00:12:24.970 --> 00:12:27.600
Besides, he says there aretwo councils kept

231
00:12:27.600 --> 00:12:29.770
and that may be determinedat the one

232
00:12:29.770 --> 00:12:32.600
which may make you and himto rue at the other.

233
00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:34.830
Therefore he sends to knowyour lordship's pleasure,

234
00:12:34.830 --> 00:12:36.570
if you will presently takehorse with him

235
00:12:36.570 --> 00:12:38.830
and with all speed postwith him toward the north

236
00:12:38.830 --> 00:12:41.100
and shun the danger thathis soul divines.

237
00:12:43.630 --> 00:12:46.100
Go, fellow, go.

238
00:12:46.100 --> 00:12:48.730
Return unto thy lord.

239
00:12:48.730 --> 00:12:52.930
Bid him not fear theseparated council.

240
00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:54.930
His honor and myself areat the one,

241
00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:57.470
and at the other is mygood friend Catesby,

242
00:12:57.470 --> 00:13:00.100
where nothing can proceedthat toucheth us

243
00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:02.670
whereof I shall not haveintelligence.

244
00:13:03.930 --> 00:13:07.300
Tell him his fears areshallow, without instance.

245
00:13:09.570 --> 00:13:12.600
And for his dreams, Iwonder he is so simple

246
00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:15.700
to trust the mockery ofunquiet slumbers.

247
00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:18.700
To fly the boar before theboar pursues

248
00:13:18.700 --> 00:13:21.200
were to incense the boarto follow us

249
00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:23.870
and make pursuit where hedid mean no chase.

250
00:13:25.230 --> 00:13:26.930
Go.

251
00:13:26.930 --> 00:13:29.870
Bid thy master rise andcome to me,

252
00:13:29.870 --> 00:13:32.200
and we will both togetherto the Tower,

253
00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:36.400
where he shall see, theboar will use us kindly.

254
00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:38.470
I'll go, my lord, and tellhim what you say.

255
00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:42.370
Oh.

256
00:13:42.370 --> 00:13:45.070
Many good morrows to mynoble lord.

257
00:13:45.070 --> 00:13:47.970
Good morrow, Catesby.

258
00:13:47.970 --> 00:13:50.700
You are early stirring.

259
00:13:50.700 --> 00:13:52.230
What news?

260
00:13:52.230 --> 00:13:55.070
What news, in this, ourtottering state?

261
00:13:55.070 --> 00:13:57.530
O, it is a reeling worldindeed, my lord.

262
00:13:57.530 --> 00:14:00.670
And I believe 'twill neverstand upright

263
00:14:00.670 --> 00:14:04.400
till Richard wear thegarland of the realm.

264
00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:06.700
How wear the garland?

265
00:14:06.700 --> 00:14:09.130
O, dost thou mean thecrown?

266
00:14:09.130 --> 00:14:10.270
Aye, my good lord.

267
00:14:11.600 --> 00:14:13.900
I'll have this crown ofmine cut from my shoulders

268
00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:16.300
before I'll see the crownso foul misplaced.

269
00:14:18.930 --> 00:14:20.530
But canst thou guess thathe doth aim at it?

270
00:14:20.530 --> 00:14:22.800
Aye, on my life.

271
00:14:22.800 --> 00:14:25.500
And hopes to find youforward upon his party

272
00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:27.100
for the gain thereof.

273
00:14:27.100 --> 00:14:29.270
And thereupon he sends youthis good news:

274
00:14:29.270 --> 00:14:32.970
that this same very day,your enemies,

275
00:14:32.970 --> 00:14:36.830
the kindred of the queen,must die at Pomfret.

276
00:14:42.700 --> 00:14:44.970
Indeed, I am no mournerfor this news...

277
00:14:46.630 --> 00:14:48.870
Because they have beenstill my adversaries.

278
00:14:51.730 --> 00:14:54.570
But that I'll give myvoice on Richard's side,

279
00:14:54.570 --> 00:14:58.100
to bar my master's heirsin true descent,

280
00:14:58.100 --> 00:14:59.670
God knows I will not doit.

281
00:14:59.670 --> 00:15:00.970
To the death.

282
00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:04.900
God keep your lordship inthat gracious mind.

283
00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:10.370
But I shall laugh at thisa twelve-month hence,

284
00:15:10.370 --> 00:15:12.700
that they which brought mein my master's hate,

285
00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:14.700
I live to look upon theirtragedy.

286
00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:20.870
O, Catesby.

287
00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:22.730
Ere a fortnight make meolder,

288
00:15:22.730 --> 00:15:24.970
I'll send some packingthat yet think not on't.

289
00:15:27.170 --> 00:15:29.670
'Tis a vile thing to die,my gracious lord,

290
00:15:29.670 --> 00:15:32.000
when men are unpreparedand look not for it.

291
00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.270
O monstrous, monstrous.

292
00:15:36.630 --> 00:15:40.370
So falls it out withRivers, Vaughan, Grey.

293
00:15:40.370 --> 00:15:42.700
And so 'twill do with somemen else

294
00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:45.370
who think themselves assafe as thou and I,

295
00:15:45.370 --> 00:15:47.900
who, as thou know'st,

296
00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:50.470
are dear to princelyRichard and to Buckingham.

297
00:15:50.470 --> 00:15:54.130
The princes both make highaccount of you,

298
00:15:54.130 --> 00:15:56.230
for they account his headupon the bridge.

299
00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:57.930
I know they do.

300
00:15:57.930 --> 00:15:59.730
And I have well deservedit.

301
00:16:01.670 --> 00:16:05.200
Come on, come on.

302
00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:07.970
Where is your boar spear,man?

303
00:16:07.970 --> 00:16:10.800
Fear you the boar and goso unprovided?

304
00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:12.230
My lord, good morrow.

305
00:16:13.430 --> 00:16:14.970
Morrow, Catesby.

306
00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:19.500
You may jest on, but bythe holy rood,

307
00:16:19.500 --> 00:16:23.200
I do not like theseseveral councils, I...

308
00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:27.800
My lord, I hold my life asdear as you.

309
00:16:27.800 --> 00:16:30.670
And never in my days, I doprotest,

310
00:16:30.670 --> 00:16:33.100
was it so precious to meas 'tis now.

311
00:16:35.430 --> 00:16:37.470
Think you but that I knowour state secure,

312
00:16:37.470 --> 00:16:40.730
I would be so triumphantas I am?

313
00:16:40.730 --> 00:16:42.070
The lords at Pomfret,

314
00:16:42.070 --> 00:16:43.900
when they rode fromLondon, were jocund

315
00:16:43.900 --> 00:16:45.770
and supposed their stateswere sure,

316
00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:49.000
and they indeed had nocause to mistrust,

317
00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.800
and yet you see how soonthe day o'ercast.

318
00:16:53.470 --> 00:16:57.170
This sudden stab of rancorI misdoubt.

319
00:17:00.670 --> 00:17:03.500
Pray God, I say, I prove aneedless coward.

320
00:17:05.770 --> 00:17:07.100
What, shall we toward theTower?

321
00:17:07.100 --> 00:17:08.330
The night is spent.

322
00:17:08.330 --> 00:17:09.800
Come, come; have with you.

323
00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:27.600
Wot you what, my lord?

324
00:17:27.600 --> 00:17:31.130
Today the lords you talkedof are beheaded.

325
00:17:37.430 --> 00:17:40.230
They for their truth mightbetter wear their heads

326
00:17:40.230 --> 00:17:42.700
than some that have accusedthem wear their hats.

327
00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:46.130
Come, my lord; let's away.

328
00:17:46.130 --> 00:17:47.130
Go on before.

329
00:17:47.130 --> 00:17:48.600
I'll talk with this goodfellow.

330
00:17:54.300 --> 00:17:56.600
Well met, Hastings.

331
00:17:57.730 --> 00:17:59.230
How goes the world withthee?

332
00:17:59.230 --> 00:18:01.900
The better that yourlordship please to ask.

333
00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:03.630
I tell thee, man, 'tisbetter with me now

334
00:18:03.630 --> 00:18:05.130
than when I met thee last.

335
00:18:05.130 --> 00:18:06.330
Where now we meet,

336
00:18:06.330 --> 00:18:07.930
then was I going prisonerto the Tower

337
00:18:07.930 --> 00:18:09.730
by the suggestion of thequeen's allies.

338
00:18:09.730 --> 00:18:12.070
But now I tell thee-- keepit to thyself--

339
00:18:12.070 --> 00:18:14.400
this day, those enemiesare put to death,

340
00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:16.700
and I in better state thane'er I was.

341
00:18:16.700 --> 00:18:18.930
God hold it to yourhonor's good content.

342
00:18:18.930 --> 00:18:21.630
Gramercy, Hastings.

343
00:18:21.630 --> 00:18:23.000
There.

344
00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.000
Drink that for me.

345
00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.430
Why, thank you, Robert.

346
00:18:26.430 --> 00:18:28.030
Well met, my lord.

347
00:18:28.030 --> 00:18:30.970
I am glad to see yourhonor.

348
00:18:30.970 --> 00:18:32.800
I thank you kindly, goodSir John.

349
00:18:34.500 --> 00:18:36.600
I am in your debt for yourlast exercise.

350
00:18:38.900 --> 00:18:41.170
Come the next Sabbath, Iwill content you.

351
00:18:44.470 --> 00:18:47.330
What, talking with apriest, lord chamberlain?

352
00:18:47.330 --> 00:18:49.770
Your friends at Pomfret,they do need the priest.

353
00:18:49.770 --> 00:18:52.600
Your honor hath noshriving work in hand.

354
00:18:52.600 --> 00:18:55.770
Good faith, and when I metthis holy man,

355
00:18:55.770 --> 00:18:57.700
the men you talked of cameinto my mind.

356
00:18:59.570 --> 00:19:01.230
What, go you toward theTower?

357
00:19:01.230 --> 00:19:02.530
I do, my lord.

358
00:19:02.530 --> 00:19:04.170
But long I cannot staythere.

359
00:19:04.170 --> 00:19:06.970
I shall return before yourlordship thence.

360
00:19:06.970 --> 00:19:09.600
Hey, like enough, for Istay dinner there.

361
00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:11.970
And supper too, althoughthou know'st it not.

362
00:19:11.970 --> 00:19:14.230
I'll wait upon yourlordship.

363
00:19:15.370 --> 00:19:17.600
Come. Shall we go?

364
00:19:17.600 --> 00:19:19.630
I'll wait upon yourlordship.

365
00:19:57.630 --> 00:20:00.930
Sir Richard Ratcliffe, letme tell thee this:

366
00:20:00.930 --> 00:20:03.630
Today shalt thou behold asubject die

367
00:20:03.630 --> 00:20:07.000
for truth, for duty, andfor loyalty!

368
00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.870
God bless the prince fromall the pack of you.

369
00:20:09.870 --> 00:20:12.300
A knot you are of damnedbloodsuckers!

370
00:20:12.300 --> 00:20:15.470
You live that shall crywoe for this hereafter!

371
00:20:15.470 --> 00:20:18.770
Dispatch; the limit ofyour lives is out.

372
00:20:26.930 --> 00:20:30.770
O Pomfret, Pomfret!

373
00:20:31.930 --> 00:20:34.600
O thou bloody prison,

374
00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:38.930
fatal and ominous to noblepeers.

375
00:20:38.930 --> 00:20:41.600
Within the guilty closureof thy walls,

376
00:20:41.600 --> 00:20:44.930
Richard II here was hackedto death.

377
00:20:44.930 --> 00:20:49.130
And for more slander tothy dismal seat,

378
00:20:49.130 --> 00:20:54.000
we give to thee ourguiltless blood to drink.

379
00:20:55.130 --> 00:20:58.630
Now Margaret's curse isfallen upon our heads

380
00:20:58.630 --> 00:21:01.930
when she exclaimed onHastings, you, and I,

381
00:21:01.930 --> 00:21:05.000
for standing by whenRichard stabbed her son.

382
00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:06.570
Then cursed she Richard.

383
00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.870
Then cursed sheBuckingham.

384
00:21:13.670 --> 00:21:16.630
Then cursed she Hastings.

385
00:21:17.930 --> 00:21:19.530
O, remember, God,

386
00:21:19.530 --> 00:21:23.570
to hear her prayer forthem as now for us

387
00:21:23.570 --> 00:21:27.100
and for my sister and herprincely sons.

388
00:21:27.100 --> 00:21:30.470
Be satisfied, dear God,with our true blood,

389
00:21:30.470 --> 00:21:34.900
which, as thou know'st,unjustly must be spilt.

390
00:21:35.530 --> 00:21:37.330
Make haste.

391
00:21:37.330 --> 00:21:39.500
The hour of death isexpiate.

392
00:21:56.530 --> 00:21:58.530
Come, Grey.

393
00:21:58.530 --> 00:22:00.230
Come, Vaughan.

394
00:22:01.670 --> 00:22:03.400
Let us here embrace.

395
00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:09.030
Farewell until we meetagain in Heaven.

396
00:22:12.930 --> 00:22:16.200
Now, noble peers, thecause why we are met

397
00:22:16.200 --> 00:22:19.200
is to determine of thecoronation.

398
00:22:19.200 --> 00:22:20.870
In God's name, speak.

399
00:22:20.870 --> 00:22:22.670
When is the royal day?

400
00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:24.700
Is all things ready forthe royal time?

401
00:22:24.700 --> 00:22:28.570
It is, and wants butnomination.

402
00:22:28.570 --> 00:22:31.100
Tomorrow, then, I judgethe happy day.

403
00:22:33.630 --> 00:22:36.900
Who knows the lordprotector's mind herein?

404
00:22:36.900 --> 00:22:39.470
Who is most inward withthe noble duke?

405
00:22:41.030 --> 00:22:43.530
Your grace, we think, shouldsoonest know his mind.

406
00:22:43.530 --> 00:22:45.230
We know each other'sfaces.

407
00:22:45.230 --> 00:22:46.530
For our hearts,

408
00:22:46.530 --> 00:22:48.830
he knows no more of minethan I of yours

409
00:22:48.830 --> 00:22:52.000
or I of his, my lord, thanyou of mine.

410
00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.870
Lord Hastings, you and heare near in love.

411
00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:59.070
I thank his grace. I knowhe loves me well.

412
00:22:59.070 --> 00:23:00.800
But for his purpose in thecoronation,

413
00:23:00.800 --> 00:23:02.400
I have not sounded him,

414
00:23:02.400 --> 00:23:06.600
nor he delivered his graciouspleasure any way therein.

415
00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:09.170
But you, my honorablelords, may name the time,

416
00:23:09.170 --> 00:23:11.800
and in the duke's behalf,I'll give my voice,

417
00:23:11.800 --> 00:23:14.700
which, I presume, he'lltake in gentle part.

418
00:23:14.700 --> 00:23:16.930
Ah, in happy time, herecomes the duke himself.

419
00:23:16.930 --> 00:23:20.370
My noble lords and cousinsall, good morrow.

420
00:23:21.930 --> 00:23:24.600
I have been long asleeper.

421
00:23:24.600 --> 00:23:27.870
But I trust my absence dothneglect no great design

422
00:23:27.870 --> 00:23:30.030
which by my presence mighthave been concluded.

423
00:23:30.030 --> 00:23:32.130
Had not you come upon yourcue, my lord,

424
00:23:32.130 --> 00:23:35.470
William, Lord Hastings,had pronounced your part--

425
00:23:35.470 --> 00:23:38.500
I mean, your voice-- forcrowning of the king.

426
00:23:39.870 --> 00:23:44.170
Than my lord Hastings, noman might be bolder.

427
00:23:44.170 --> 00:23:47.030
His lordship knows me welland loves me well.

428
00:23:53.630 --> 00:23:55.570
My lord of Ely.

429
00:23:55.570 --> 00:23:56.830
When I was last inHolborn,

430
00:23:56.830 --> 00:23:59.470
I saw good strawberries inyour garden there.

431
00:23:59.470 --> 00:24:01.370
I do beseech you send forsome of them.

432
00:24:01.370 --> 00:24:03.170
Marry, and will, my lord,with all my heart.

433
00:24:06.530 --> 00:24:08.870
Cousin of Buckingham, aword with you.

434
00:24:13.070 --> 00:24:15.970
Catesby hath soundedHastings in our business

435
00:24:15.970 --> 00:24:18.400
and finds the testygentleman so hot

436
00:24:18.400 --> 00:24:20.930
that he will lose his headere give consent

437
00:24:20.930 --> 00:24:24.430
his master's child, asworshipfully he terms it,

438
00:24:24.430 --> 00:24:27.100
shall lose the royalty ofEngland's throne.

439
00:24:28.730 --> 00:24:30.170
Withdraw yourself awhile.

440
00:24:30.170 --> 00:24:31.500
I'll go with you.

441
00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:48.100
We have not yet set downthis day of triumph.

442
00:24:48.100 --> 00:24:51.770
Tomorrow, in my judgment,is too sudden,

443
00:24:51.770 --> 00:24:53.500
for I myself am not sowell provided

444
00:24:53.500 --> 00:24:55.800
as else I would be werethe day prolonged.

445
00:24:58.270 --> 00:24:59.870
Where is my lord, the dukeof Gloucester?

446
00:24:59.870 --> 00:25:02.030
I have sent for thesestrawberries.

447
00:25:11.100 --> 00:25:14.770
His grace looks cheerfullyand smooth today.

448
00:25:14.770 --> 00:25:16.900
There's some conceit orother likes him well

449
00:25:16.900 --> 00:25:18.900
when that he bids goodmorrow with such spirit.

450
00:25:20.100 --> 00:25:21.700
I think there's never aman in Christendom

451
00:25:21.700 --> 00:25:24.170
can lesser hide his loveor hate than he,

452
00:25:24.170 --> 00:25:27.600
for by his face, straightshall you know his heart.

453
00:25:27.600 --> 00:25:30.100
What of his heart perceiveyou in his face

454
00:25:30.100 --> 00:25:32.070
by any livelihood heshowed today?

455
00:25:32.070 --> 00:25:35.200
Marry, that with no manhere he is offended.

456
00:25:35.200 --> 00:25:38.070
For were he, he had shownit in his looks.

457
00:25:38.070 --> 00:25:40.700
I pray God he be not, Isay.

458
00:25:59.400 --> 00:26:01.970
I pray you all,

459
00:26:01.970 --> 00:26:04.930
tell me what they deservethat do conspire my death

460
00:26:04.930 --> 00:26:07.630
with devilish plots ofdamned witchcraft

461
00:26:07.630 --> 00:26:09.600
and that have prevailedupon my body

462
00:26:09.600 --> 00:26:11.330
with their hellish charms.

463
00:26:14.470 --> 00:26:17.730
The tender love I bearyour grace, my lord,

464
00:26:17.730 --> 00:26:20.430
makes me most forward inthis princely presence

465
00:26:20.430 --> 00:26:23.900
to doom the offenders,whatsoe'er they be.

466
00:26:24.970 --> 00:26:27.400
I say, my lord, they havedeserved death.

467
00:26:27.400 --> 00:26:29.970
Then be your eyes thewitness of their evil.

468
00:26:31.770 --> 00:26:33.270
See how I am bewitched.

469
00:26:35.770 --> 00:26:37.330
Behold.

470
00:26:37.330 --> 00:26:40.700
Mine arm is, like a blastedsapling, withered up.

471
00:26:41.930 --> 00:26:44.800
And this is Edward's wife,that monstrous witch,

472
00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:47.470
consorted with that harlotstrumpet Shore,

473
00:26:47.470 --> 00:26:50.530
that by their witchcraftthus have marked me.

474
00:26:50.530 --> 00:26:52.800
If they have done thisdeed, my noble lord--

475
00:26:52.800 --> 00:26:55.870
If! Thou protector of thisdamned strumpet!

476
00:26:55.870 --> 00:26:57.900
Talk'st thou to me of"ifs"?

477
00:26:57.900 --> 00:26:59.200
Thou art a traitor.

478
00:26:59.200 --> 00:27:00.570
Off with his head!

479
00:27:00.570 --> 00:27:02.030
Now by Saint Paul, Iswear,

480
00:27:02.030 --> 00:27:03.970
I will not dine until Isee the same.

481
00:27:03.970 --> 00:27:05.800
Lovel and Ratcliffe, lookthat it be done.

482
00:27:05.800 --> 00:27:07.870
The rest that love me,rise and follow me.

483
00:27:42.830 --> 00:27:44.500
O woe.

484
00:27:47.470 --> 00:27:48.870
Woe for England.

485
00:27:50.530 --> 00:27:53.430
Not a whit for me.

486
00:27:53.430 --> 00:27:57.030
For I, too fond, mighthave prevented this.

487
00:27:57.030 --> 00:28:00.270
Stanley did dream the boardid raze his helm.

488
00:28:02.100 --> 00:28:04.870
And I did scorn it anddistained to fly.

489
00:28:07.270 --> 00:28:10.670
Three times today, myfoot-cloth horse did stumble

490
00:28:10.670 --> 00:28:14.030
and started when he lookedupon the Tower,

491
00:28:14.030 --> 00:28:16.570
as loath to bear me to theslaughterhouse.

492
00:28:19.430 --> 00:28:23.070
Oh, now I need the priestthat spake to me.

493
00:28:25.770 --> 00:28:28.570
I now repent I told thepursuivant as too triumphing

494
00:28:28.570 --> 00:28:32.430
how mine enemies today atPomfret bloodily werebutchered

495
00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:35.630
and I myself secure ingrace and favor.

496
00:28:40.900 --> 00:28:44.600
Oh, Margaret, Margaret.

497
00:28:46.730 --> 00:28:51.530
Now thy heavy curse islighted on poor Hastings'wretched head.

498
00:28:51.530 --> 00:28:53.000
Come, come, dispatch.

499
00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:55.270
The duke would be atdinner.

500
00:28:55.270 --> 00:28:56.330
Make a short shrift.

501
00:28:56.330 --> 00:28:58.030
He longs to see your head.

502
00:29:01.270 --> 00:29:05.630
O momentary grace ofmortal men,

503
00:29:05.630 --> 00:29:10.300
which we more hunt forthan the grace of God.

504
00:29:10.300 --> 00:29:12.930
Who builds his hope in airof your good looks

505
00:29:12.930 --> 00:29:15.900
lives like a drunkensailor on a mast,

506
00:29:15.900 --> 00:29:17.930
ready with every nod totumble down

507
00:29:17.930 --> 00:29:20.500
into the fatal bowels ofthe deep.

508
00:29:20.500 --> 00:29:22.300
Come, come, dispatch.

509
00:29:22.300 --> 00:29:23.930
'Tis bootless to exclaim.

510
00:29:23.930 --> 00:29:25.300
Bloody Richard!

511
00:29:29.670 --> 00:29:31.200
Miserable England.

512
00:29:33.900 --> 00:29:36.500
I prophesy the fearfulesttime to thee

513
00:29:36.500 --> 00:29:38.630
that ever wretched agehath looked upon.

514
00:29:48.500 --> 00:29:50.470
Come.

515
00:29:50.470 --> 00:29:52.970
Lead me to the block.

516
00:29:52.970 --> 00:29:55.970
Bear him my head.

517
00:29:55.970 --> 00:29:58.400
They smile at me whoshortly shall be dead.

518
00:30:31.830 --> 00:30:33.130
Come, cousin.

519
00:30:33.130 --> 00:30:35.330
Canst thou quake andchange thy color,

520
00:30:35.330 --> 00:30:37.430
murder thy breath in themiddle of a word,

521
00:30:37.430 --> 00:30:39.200
and then again begin andstop again

